-- ARM, BP, Lloyds Banking, Prudential May Move: U.K., Irish Equity Preview
-- Sarah Jones
-- 2010-04-27T06:45:24Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-04-27/arm-bp-lloyds-banking-prudential-u-k-irish-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following is a list of
companies whose shares may have unusual price changes in U.K.
and Irish markets today. Stock symbols are in parentheses and
prices are from the last market close.  
 The benchmark FTSE 100 Index rose 30.2, or 0.5 percent, to
5,753.85. The FTSE All-Share Index advanced 0.6 percent and
Ireland’s ISEQ Index climbed 1.1 percent.  
 ARM Holdings Plc (ARM LN): The designer of semiconductors
used in Apple Inc.’s iPhone reported a rise in first-quarter
revenue to 92.3 million pounds from 79.9 million pounds a year
earlier. That beat the average analyst estimate of 89.1 million
pounds, according to Bloomberg data.  
 The shares rose 4.2 pence, or 1.7 percent, to 258.6 pence.  
 BP Plc (BP/ LN): The oil company said profit more than
doubled in the first quarter to $6.08 billion on higher oil
prices. Excluding gains or losses from holding inventories and
one-time items, earnings beat analyst estimates. The stock fell
12.9 pence, or 2 percent, to 626.8 pence.  
 Connaught Plc (CNT LN): The biggest U.K. public housing
maintenance company reported a 17 percent rise in first-half
revenue to 355 million pounds. The shares rose 4 pence, or 1.5
percent, to 277 pence.  
 Hargreaves Lansdown Plc (HL/ LN): Peter Hargreaves will
step down as chief executive officer of Hargreaves Lansdown Plc,
29 years after he helped start Britain’s biggest retail
brokerage. The shares fell 7.7 pence, or 2 percent, to 373.3
pence.  
 Imperial Tobacco Group Plc (IMT LN): The cigarette maker
reported a first-half profit of 689 million pounds versus a loss
of 149 million pounds a year earlier. The stock declined 6
pence, or 0.3 percent, to 1,947 pence.  
 Lloyds Banking Group Plc (LLOY LN): The U.K.’s biggest
mortgage lender said it returned to profit in the first quarter
of this year as impairments fell. The bank also said in a
statement that its financial performance will be better than
previously guided. The shares rose 1.76 pence, or 2.6 percent,
to 70.24 pence.  
 Prudential Plc (PRU LN): Capital Group Cos., Prudential
Plc’s biggest shareholder, has approached three U.K.-based
insurers to gauge their interest in a group bid for the company,
the London-based Times reported, without attribution. The stock
rose 5 pence, or 0.9 percent, to 546 pence.  
